<p class="style1">Why LA Needs This Park 
</p>
<p>The city&rsquo;s plans to build a new police headquarters on the old Caltrans
  site and the neighboring block anchored by St. Vibiana&rsquo;s will squander
  the ideal site for a major civic park for Los Angeles and will undermine emerging
  arts and cultural movements downtown. </p>
<p>The city&rsquo;s abrupt selection of this architecturally and historically
  significant site for a police headquarters disregarded longstanding plans and
  council motions calling for open space on the block. And it landed just as
  hard-won gains in urban renewal have begun to bring thousands of new residents
  and businesses downtown.</p>
<p>The city plan for the old Caltrans site shows an 11-story, 500,000-square-foot
  headquarters, an auditorium, parking for 700 police vehicles and a small community
  park. On the block anchored by St. Vibiana&rsquo;s would be parking for another
  500 police vehicles and the motor pool where police cars are washed and serviced. </p>
<p>This massive project would permanently alter the potential of the area to
  develop into a commercial and pedestrian friendly zone that would help the
  arts community and surrounding neighborhoods succeed. The council made its
  decision June 23, 2004, without public discussion or input from those most
  directly affected.</p>
<p>Hundreds have since protested at public meetings in August, October and November.
  More than 1,000 have signed a protest petition. </p>
<p>The city&rsquo;s Cultural Affairs Commission, which has the responsibility
  for approving all architectural proposals on city property, reviewed the plans
  and took public comment. It voted at its Jan 20 meeting against approving the
  plans for the police headquarters on the site. And, on Feb. 3, the commission
  passed a motion asking the City Council to revisit its decision.</p>
<p><span class="style1">Impact on the arts community would be dramatic</span><br>

  The block at 1st, 2nd, Spring and Main streets marks the start of Gallery Row,
    the arts initiative along Main and Spring streets that in less than a year
    has grown from 4 galleries to 15. Across the street is historic St. Vibiana's,
    built in 1876. The former cathedral &ndash; narrowly saved from an earlier
    wrecking ball &ndash; has just undergone a $6 million renovation and transformation
    into an arts center. On the other side of Main, the Linda Lea Theater is
about to be renovated and re-opened as a film and performance arts venue. </p>
<p>Works of art, art fairs and festivals in the park were to have played a key
  role in bringing people into the area and supporting these city-backed arts
  endeavors.<br>

  Under the city's current plan, not only would there be no park to showcase
  artwork and attract crowds, the building on Main where the Gallery Row concept
  was born -- formerly Inshallah, now MJ Higgins &ndash; would be torn down to
  make space for police parking and a motor pool. The plan leaves virtually no
  public parking in the area for arts, restaurant and shop patrons.</p>
<p>Allowed to thrive, these important cultural initiatives will help create a
  lively, authentic arts district that bridges the established art museums just
  east and west -- MOCA, the Geffen Contemporary and the Japanese American National
  Museum -- and the Music Center's performing arts venues up the hill. <br>

</p>
<p><span class="style1">A historic opportunity to give the citizens of LA a place
    in the city&rsquo;s
  civic center.</span><br>

  Public parks and civic gathering places are hallmarks of great cities but Los
  Angeles has grown up with almost none. The old Caltrans block gives us a rare
  opportunity to dramatically change that &ndash; the kind of chance that comes
  along once in 100 years if we&rsquo;re lucky. Urban planners and city officials
  have repeatedly identified it as ideal for a great public space. At the steps
  of City Hall, it is the public&rsquo;s gateway to its government and it is
  the city&rsquo;s gateway to its historic core, business districts and growing
  residential and arts corridors. The police building proposed for the site would
  visually and emotionally close off that connection. Creating a park would nourish
  it and extend a long-overdue welcome to residents of this far-flung city, so
  in need of common ground. Bordering the site are LA&rsquo;s earliest thoroughfares
  and some of its oldest and newest landmarks &ndash; including City Hall, the
  LA Times, St. Vibiana&rsquo;s, the new Caltrans building, and, just up the
  street, Disney Hall. How this block is used will in many ways define the kind
  of city we become. </p>
<p><span class="style1">For more than a decade, this block has been identified as ideal for public
  open space</span><br>

  The Master Plan for civic center development adopted by the City Council in
  1997 shows this block as eventual open space. Subsequent Council motions echo
  and support that plan. In 2000 and 2001, when the Council approved the land
  swap that gives LA ownership of this block, its motions repeatedly talked of
  the opportunity for open space. The swap would allow the city to use the &ldquo;property
  directly across from the First Street entrance to City Hall &hellip; for added
  green space in the Civic Center area.&rdquo; Private property on the block
  was subject to condemnation because &ldquo;the public interest and necessity
  require the acquisition of real property for the creation of open space.&rdquo; Once
  the new Caltrans building was completed, the Council said, the city will &ldquo;convert
  the block directly across from the First Street Steps of City Hall into open
  space.&rdquo;<br>

  Just six weeks before the vote to put the police headquarters on the block,
  an advisory committee of community leaders was named to help plan for a park.
  Named as co-chairs were Aileen Adams and Adele Yellin, whose late husband,
  Ira, conceptualized the park as a key component of a reinvigorated urban center.</p>
<p><span class="style1">Workers, residents and downtown&rsquo;s children need
  a healthy, welcoming park.</span><br>

  This site is close to thousands of downtown workers and a growing number of
  residents who need park space to help them lead healthy lives. In a densely
  populated area, cities have a critical responsibility to ensure that there
  is park space where people can gather, jog, relax and breath a little easier &ndash; and
  where children have a safe place to play. Two-thirds of Los Angeles children
  do not live within walking distance of a public park &ndash; the ratio is even
  worse downtown.<br>

  Creating a park on this site would radically improve the environment for those
  who work and live in the surrounding districts and all who come to visit. </p>
<p><span class="style1">A park on this site will foster sustainable business and residential development.</span><br>

  Little Tokyo, the Historic Core, Artists, Toy, Broadway, Bunker Hill and Grand
  Avenue districts will all benefit if pedestrians and other visitors can move
  easily from one area to another. This site has the unique potential to help
  bring these interests together in a critical mass of arts venues, restaurants
  and other businesses. Human-friendly public spaces will help ensure the success
  of downtown redevelopment that will in turn generate tax revenue and other
  benefits for the entire city. Many of the 8,000 new downtown housing units
  in the pipeline or under consideration are near this site.</p>
<p><span class="style1">A great civic park in downtown LA will be a point of pride for generations
  to come. </span><br>

  Backers of this park envision a place as extraordinary as this city. The design
  possibilities have already generated interest around the world. One concept
  shows it with a great artwork &ndash; a palm spiral envisioned by the late
  artist Robert Smithson. Most see it with multiple uses, dynamic attractions
  and with an underground parking facility to accommodate visitors. All see it
  as a place where people from LA&rsquo;s many and diverse communities can gather
  and enjoy their city. </p>
<p><span class="style1">All sites are not created equal &ndash; and this one
    is unique.</span> <br>

  There is no other site so well suited for a great civic park for Los Angeles.
    In addition to its keystone location, the old Caltrans site is on level ground
    and is open and welcoming from all sides. The decision to put the LAPD headquarters
    here did not take into consideration its enormous value if developed differently.
    The size and requirements of the police project will dominate not just one,
    but two key blocks in the very heart of the city. The police facility requires
    security setbacks, there can be no parking beneath the headquarters, access
    must be tightly controlled, operations must exist in specialized configurations &ndash; in
    short, defensible space must be created. While these are important security
    considerations, they preclude more neighbor-friendly uses. </p>
<p><span class="style1">The city selected this site for the police headquarters without a public conversation
  about it.</span><br>

  The appropriateness of the Caltrans site for a police headquarters was never
  the subject of a public hearing in advance of the City Council&rsquo;s decision.
  There was no notice that this site would be the subject of a vote at the council
  meeting. There was no opportunity before the vote for public input on the site&rsquo;s
  architectural and historic significance, and no opportunity to demonstrate
  the good for the city that would come from a park on this site. There was no
  opportunity to remind the council of its previous motions in support of creating
  open space on the block. And no opportunity for public discussion of the impact
  the facility would have on arts and cultural development. The decision was
  not even the subject of its own motion. It came as an amendment to the motion
  removing the 1st and Alameda property in Little Tokyo from consideration. </p>
<p><span class="style1">From wrong location to wrong location: It&rsquo;s time
    to find the right site for the LAPD. </span><br>

  There are alternative sites suitable for a new police headquarters &ndash; and
  the city needs to redouble efforts to identify them. The City Council listened
  when residents and businesses in Little Tokyo and the Artists District protested
  that putting the facility at 1st and Alameda would disrupt renewal efforts
  in those communities. But then the Council voted to put the police facility
  on this even more sensitive site. It is time for city officials to develop
  a plan that gives the LAPD the headquarters it needs and supports rather than
  disrupts the real yet fragile urban renewal taking place downtown. We believe
  that a site exists that will serve the LAPD better than this one &ndash; and
  without sacrificing other important goals for building a strong and vibrant
  city. And the sooner the city focuses on identifying the right site, the sooner
  genuine progress can be made.<br>

  This is a decision that must be bigger than any individual interests. It must
  be about taking the long view &ndash; and about being caretakers of the future. </p>
<p class="style1">We ask you to join us in envisioning that future -- and a new dynamic for
LA. </p>
